www.tensorflow.org/versions/r0.7/api_docs/python/framework.html#Graph.name_scope\" rel=\"nofollow\">example in the docs</a> shows how to re-enter the original scope from within a nested scope - but not when context is closed.</p>\n<p>Perhaps this could be solved by enabling access to the scope reference as <code>tf.Variable.scope</code> ?</p>\n<p>Current hack-y workaround is to manually specify variable name as <code>\"{}/name\".format(previous_scope_name)</code></p>", "body_text": "As far as I can tell, there is no way to re-enter the same name_scope or variable_scope (once closed) without the name being \"unique-ified.\"\nThe example in the docs shows how to re-enter the original scope from within a nested scope - but not when context is closed.\nPerhaps this could be solved by enabling access to the scope reference as tf.Variable.scope ?\nCurrent hack-y workaround is to manually specify variable name as \"{}/name\".format(previous_scope_name)", "body": "As far as I can tell, there is no way to re-enter the same name_scope or variable_scope (once closed) without the name being \"unique-ified.\"\n\nThe [example in the docs](https://www.tensorflow.org/versions/r0.7/api_docs/python/framework.html#Graph.name_scope) shows how to re-enter the original scope from within a nested scope - but not when context is closed.\n\nPerhaps this could be solved by enabling access to the scope reference as `tf.Variable.scope` ?\n\nCurrent hack-y workaround is to manually specify variable name as `\"{}/name\".format(previous_scope_name)`\n"}